d within hours of his murder on September 22nd when three mosques were attacked with petrol bombs.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=Reporter|first=Staff|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/Islamic-organisations-blame-police-for-violence-in-Coimbatore/article15422251.ece|title=Islamic organisations blame police for violence in Coimbatore|date=2016-10-02|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Mobs-go-on-rampage-at-funeral-of-Hindu-activist-in-Coimbatore/articleshow/54492105.cms|title=Mobs go on rampage at funeral of Hindu activist in Coimbatore {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Sep 24|first=A. Subburaj {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated|last2=2016|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30|last3=Ist|first3=08:22}}</ref>\n\nDuring the funeral procession of Sasikumar from CMCH to Subramaniampalayam, mobs mostly of Hindu munnani members, started destroying the window panes of several shops and attacked several houses and commercial establishments mostly of Muslims, along their way.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> The members also pelted stones at the buses and shops and attacked several places of worship creating chaos.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Madhavan|first=Karthik|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/%E2%80%8BMurder-of-Hindu-Munnani-functionary-sparks-communal-violence-in-Coimbatore/article14995576.ece|title=\u200bMurder of Hindu Munnani functionary sparks communal violence in Coimbatore|date=2016-09-23|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|url-status=live|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> When the procession reached the [[Thudiyalur]], where Sasikumar lived, the mob turned their rage at the police and started pelting stones at the police which injured 12 policemen and also burned a Police jeep.<ref name=\":2\" /> Media persons covering the funeral procession were also attacked and three police officers also sustained burn injuries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/pti-feed/story/hindu-munnani-functionary-hacked-to-death-bandh-turns-violent-692387-2016-09-23|title=Hindu Munnani functionary hacked to death, bandh turns violent|last=September 23|first=P. T. I.|last2=September 23|first2=2016UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30|last3=Ist|first3=2016 20:20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/hindu-munnani-functionary-succumbs-to-burns-116100800470_1.html|title=Hindu Munnani functionary succumbs to burns|date=2016-10-08|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe mob also set several cars on fire and some members set fire and ransacked several Shops.<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/bandh-called-by-hindu-munnani-turns-violent-116092300908_1.html|title=Bandh called by Hindu Munnani turns violent|date=2016-09-23|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> 1 Police jeep and an auto-rickshaw were burned down and at least 30 government buses were damaged by the rioters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/hindu-activists-murder-after-riots-calm-in-coimbatore/17637176|title=Hindu activist's murder: After riots, calm in Coimbatore|date=2016-09-25|website=mid-day|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Eyewitness claimed that the mob went on a looting spree even in-front of the watching police.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nA Muslim man's mobile phone shop at Tutiyalur was looted and ransacked allegedly by members of [[Hindutva]] outfits after they broke into the shop at the night of September 24th. The CCTV video of the looting quickly went viral on social media. Members of the Muslim Community alleged that Muslim businesses were mostly targeted by the rioters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/coimbatore-violence-cctv-footage-muslim-mans-mobile-phone-shop-being-looted-50399|title=Coimbatore violence: CCTV footage of Muslim man's mobile phone shop being looted|last=|first=|date=|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nTensions also prevailed in [[Tiruppur]] and most of the Shops were closed down in both the cities during the rampage. Some schools were also closed. Six special police teams have been formed to catch the rioters.\u00a0Meanwhile Muslim\u00a0organizations asked the collector for an intervention by district administration to end the violence by HIndutva outfits.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Damages ==\nA joint petition by the Forum for Coimbatore People\u2019s Unity including several advocate's and political parties to the district collector on January 2019, reported that the rioters of the [[Hindu Munnani]] had damaged 10 private vehicles, 34 government buses, 39 shops belonging to Muslims, 15 shops belonging to the Hindus and 6 Police Vehicles. The report estimated the damages to about 5 crores.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/get-rs-5cr-from-hindu-munnani-for-damage-caused-during-riot/articleshow/67647768.cms|title='Get Rs 5cr from Hindu Munnani for damage caused during riot' {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Jan 22|last2=2019|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30|last3=Ist|first3=23:40}}</ref> The petition asked the district administration to collect 5 crores from Hindu Munnani and also accused the Hindu Munnani of trying to get political gains from the riots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nyoooz.com/news/coimbatore/1308755/get-rs-5cr-from-hindu-munnani-for-damage-caused-during-riot/|title='Get Rs 5cr from Hindu Munnani for damage caused during riot' {{!}} Coimbatore NYOOOZ|last=NYOOOZ|website=NYOOOZ|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Arrests ==\nThe Coimbatore police reported that it had arrested more than 650 people involved in the unrest on September 26th. Of them 129 remained in custody for allegedly planning violence and involvement in violence and the remaining were given bail. The police also warned that the number would go up.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Ananth|first=M. k|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Coimbatore/Coimbatore-unrest-650-arrested/article14999697.ece|title=Coimbatore unrest: 650 arrested|date=2016-09-26|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.india.com/news/india/coimbatore-bandh-more-than-100-protesters-of-hindu-munnani-arrested-for-rioting-after-murder-of-their-leader-1511174/|title=Coimbatore bandh: More than 100 protesters of Hindu Munnani arrested for rioting after murder of their leader|last=Desk|first=India com News|date=2016-09-24|website=India.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn October 2016, Two members of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] were arrested for their involvement in the riots under the [[Goonda Acts|Goondas Act]] and were sent to the [[Vellore Central Prison]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/coimbatore/Funeral-procession-violence-2-BJP-cadres-slapped-with-Goondas-Act/articleshow/54887829.cms|title=Funeral procession violence: 2 BJP cadres slapped with Goondas Act {{!}} Coimbatore News - Times of India|last=Oct 17|first=TNN {{!}}|last2=2016|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30|last3=Ist|first3=03:16}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nDirector general of police, Ramesh. K Ramanujam said that there is an issue in the investigation for the case, because not every murder was communal in nature and a series of murders in the state for the past few years have been given communal colour by Hindutva groups in an attempt to spread their ideologies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/not-all-attacks-on-hindu-leaders-communal-tamil-nadu-dgp/article4956148.ece|title=Not all attacks on Hindu leaders communal: Tamil Nadu DGP|date=2013-07-26|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> A senior police officer said that some members of Hindutva outfits have known criminal records and when caught they try to use their religion to escape from the law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/817527/in-coimbatore-a-murder-and-mob-action-expose-the-hate-politics-of-fringe-religious-groups|title=In Coimbatore, a murder and mob action expose the hate politics of fringe religious groups|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:2016 in India]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n\n{{TamilNadu-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lam-ang", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixedCS1 error", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Coimbatore_riots"}
{"title_page": "Serbia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2019", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox song contest national year\n| Contest                = Junior\n| Year                   = 2019\n| Country                = Serbia\n| Preselection           = Internal selection\n| Preselection date      = 16 September 2019\n| Entrant                = Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107\n| Song                   = Podigni glas (Raise Your Voice)\n| Writer                 = Aleksandra Milutinovi\u0107<br>[[Leontina Vukomanovi\u0107]]<br>Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107<br>Aleksandar Sabli\u0107\n| SF result              = \n| Final result           = 10th, 109 points\n}}\n'''Serbia''' participated in the '''[[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2019]]''' in [[Gliwice]], [[Poland]] with the song \"Podigni glas (Raise Your Voice)\" performed by Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107. [[Radio Television of Serbia]] (RTS) was responsible for selecting their entry for the contest.\n\n==Background==\n{{main|Serbia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest}}\nPrior to the 2019 Contest, Serbia had participated in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest eight times since its debut in {{Escyr|2006|Junior}},<ref name=\"Serbia History\">{{cite web|title=Junior Eurovision Song Contest: Serbia|url=http://www.junioreurovision.tv/page/country-profile?country=51|website=junioreurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref> and once as {{Esccnty|Serbia and Montenegro|Junior}} in {{Escyr|2005|Junior}},<ref>{{cite web|last1=Philips|first1=Roel|title=Serbia & Montenegro, Lithuania and Ukraine join in Hasselt|url=http://esctoday.com/4806/serbia__montenegro_lithuania_and_ukraine_join_in_hasselt|website=esctoday.com|publisher=ESCToday|accessdate=31 August 2016|date=2 August 2005}}</ref> prior to the [[Montenegrin independence referendum, 2006|Montenegrin independence referendum in 2006]] which culminated into the dissolution of Serbia and Montenegro,<ref name=N1>[[Dieter Nohlen|Nohlen, D]] & St\u00f6ver, P (2010) ''Elections in Europe: A data handbook'', p1372 {{ISBN|978-3-8329-5609-7}}</ref> As of 2019, Serbia's best results are two third places, achieved in {{Escyr|2007|Junior}} and {{Escyr|2010|Junior}}. In [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018|last year's contest]] Serbia got a nineteenth place with [[Serbia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018#Bojana Radovanovi\u0107|Bojana Radovanovi\u0107]] and a song called \"[[Serbia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2017#Svet|Svet]]\".\n\n==Before Junior Eurovision==\nOn 16 September 2019, it was announced that Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107 would represent the country in [[Gliwice]], [[Poland]] with a song called \"Podigni glas\".<ref name=\"Darija\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/rts/ci/%D0%95%D0%B2%D1%80%D0%BE%D1%81%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B3/junior/story/3081/decja-pesma-evrovizije-2019/3662160/izabran-je-predstavnik-srbije-za-takmicenje-junior-eurovision-song-contest-2019.html|title=\u0418\u0437\u0430\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d \u0458\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0421\u0440\u0431\u0438\u0458\u0435 \u0437\u0430 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u045a\u0435 \"Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2019\"|date=16 September 2019|website=rts.rs}}</ref>\n\n==Artist and song information==\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107\n| image            = Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107 2019.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| origin           = [[Belgrade]], Serbia\n| instrument       = Vocals\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = Singer, voice actress\n| years_active     = \n| label            = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=y|2007|10|27}}\n| death_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[Belgrade]], Serbia\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = \n| current_members  = \n| past_members     = \n| notable_instruments = \n}}\n{{Infobox song contest entry\n| junior         = yes\n| song           = {{Flagicon|Serbia}} \"Podigni glas (Raise Your Voice)\"\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| year           = 2019\n| country        = Serbia\n| artist         = Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107\n| as             = \n| with           = \n| languages      = {{Hlist|[[Serbian language|Serbian]]|[[English language|English]]}}\n| composer       = {{hlist|Aleksandra Milutinovi\u0107|Leontina Vukomanovi\u0107|Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107|Aleksandar Sabli\u0107}}\n| lyricist       = {{hlist|Aleksandra Milutinovi\u0107|Leontina Vukomanovi\u0107|Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107|Aleksandar Sabli\u0107}}\n| place          = 10\n| points         = 109\n| lyrics         =\n| prev_year      = 2018\n| prev           = Svet\n| prev_link      = Serbia in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018#Svet\n| next           =\n| next_link      =\n}}\n===Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107===\n'''Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107''' (born 27 October 2007) is a Serbian child singer. She represented Serbia at the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2019 with the song \"Podigni glas\".\n\n===Podigni glas (Raise Your Voice)===\n\"'''Podigni glas'''\" ({{lang-sr|\u041f\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0438 \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441}}; lit. Raise your voice) is a song by Serbian singer Darija Vra\u010devi\u0107. It represented Serbia at the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2019.\n\n==At Junior Eurovision==\nDuring the opening ceremony and the running order draw which both took place on 18 November 2019, Serbia was drawn to perform nineteenth (last) on 24 November 2019, following Albania.\n\n===Voting===\nThe results of the 2019 Junior Eurovision Song Contest were determined by national juries and an online audience vote. Every country had a national jury that consisted of three music industry professionals and two kids aged between 10 and 15 who were citizens of the country they represented. This jury was asked to judge each contestant based on: vocal capacity; the stage performance; the song's composition and originality; and the overall impression by the act. In addition, no member of a national jury could be related in any way to any of the competing acts in such a way that they could not vote impartially and independently. The first phase of the online voting begun on 22 November 2019 when a recap of all the rehearsal performances was shown on ''junioreurovision.tv'' before the viewers could vote. After this, voters also had the option to watch longer one-minute clips from each participant\u2019s rehearsal. This first round of voting stopped on Sunday, 24 November, at 15:59 CET. The second phase of the online voting took place during the live show and begun right after the last performance and was open for 15 minutes. International viewers could vote for a minimum of three countries and a maximum of five. They could also vote for their own country\u2019s song. These votes were then turned into points which were be determined by the percentage of votes received. For example, if a song received 20% of the votes, it received 20% of the available points. The public vote counted for 50% of the final result, while the other 50% came from the professional juries.\n\n===Points awarded to Serbia===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"| Jury\n|-\n!width=20%|12 points\n!width=20%|10 points\n!width=20%|8 points\n!width=20%|7 points\n!width=20%|6 points\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|North Macedonia|Junior|y=2019}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|France|Junior|y=2019}}\n|-\n!width=20%|5 points\n!width=20%|4 points\n!width=20%|3 points\n!width=20%|2 points\n!width=20%|1 point\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Albania|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Kazakhstan|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Spain|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Wales|Junior|y=2019}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Ireland|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Netherlands|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Russia|Junior|y=2019}}\n| valign=\"top\" |\n| valign=\"top\" |\n*{{Esc|Belarus|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Georgia|Junior|y=2019}}\n*{{Esc|Ukraine|Junior|y=2019}}\n|}\n\n* Serbia received 63 points from Online voting.\n\n===Points awarded by Serbia===\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"gold\"|'''12 points'''||{{Esc|Kazakhstan|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"silver\"|'''10 points'''||{{Esc|Poland|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20% bgcolor=\"#CC9966\"|'''8 points'''||{{Esc|France|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''7 points'''||{{Esc|Australia|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''6 points'''||{{Esc|Italy|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''5 points'''||{{Esc|Spain|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''4 points'''||{{Esc|Georgia|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''3 points'''||{{Esc|Ukraine|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''2 points'''||{{Esc|North Macedonia|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|width=20%|'''1 point'''||{{Esc|Malta|y=2019|Junior}}\n|-\n|}\n====Split voting results====\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!colspan=10| Split voting results from Serbia\n|-\n! Draw\n! Country\n! <small>Juror 1\n! <small>Juror 2\n! <small>Juror 3\n! <small>Juror 4\n! <small>Juror 5\n! Average Rank\n! Points\n|-\n| 01\n| align=\"left\"| {{Esc|Australia|y=2019|Junior}}\n| 4\n| 5\n| 6\n| 8\n| 4\n| 4\n| 7\n|-\n| 02\n| align=\"left\"| {{Esc|France|y=2019|Junior}}\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 3\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 3\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 3\n|bgcolor=\"silver\" | 2\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 3\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 3\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 8\n|-\n| 03\n| align=\"left\"| {{Esc|Russia|y=2019|Junior}}\n| 11\n| 9\n| 9\n| 17\n| 8\n| 12\n| bgcolor=\"#AAAAAA\"|\n|-\n| 04\n| align=\"left\"| {{Esc|North Macedonia|y=2019|Junior}}\n| 18\n| 8\n| 17\n| bgcolor=\"#CC9966\" | 3\n| 18\n| 9\n| 2\n|-\n| 05\n| align=\"left\"| {{Esc|Spain|y=2019|Junior}}\n| 9\n| 6\n| 7\n| 5\n| 5\n| 6\n| 5\n|-\n| 06\n| align=\"left\"| {{Esc|